    "narrative": "## Rough Opening Day: 1-3, Down 52%\n\nNot the start we wanted. The model went 1-3 with a brutal -52% return, getting caught on the wrong side of three unders that sailed over the number.\n\n## HIGH CONFIDENCE\n\nOur lone high confidence play was **Nationals @ Cubs OVER 9.5**, which closed at 9 runs flat. The model projected 11 runs based on shaky starting pitching \u2014 the Cubs starter came in with a 4.94 expected fielding independent pitching mark, while Washington's wasn't much better at 3.98. Decent hitting conditions with 62\u00b0F temps and a mild crosswind. But the game stayed under control and finished at 9, a 2-run miss that falls within normal variance for opening day rust.\n\n## MEDIUM CONFIDENCE\n\nThe medium tier went 1-2, and two of those losses were significant misses. \n\n***** BIG MISS ***** **Twins @ Orioles UNDER 8.5** was the worst of the night \u2014 projected 7 runs, actual 14, a massive 7-run gap. Both starters had solid expected metrics (3.97 and 4.09), but something broke down badly. With no pace or environmental red flags in the pregame data, this looks like either the bullpens imploded early or the starting pitchers' spring metrics didn't translate to regular season sharpness. Opening day can expose guys who aren't truly ready.\n\n***** BIG MISS ***** **Rangers @ Phillies UNDER 8.0** was another painful one \u2014 projected 6.8 runs, actual 11, a 4.2-run gap. The pregame setup looked solid with Philadelphia's starter at 3.83 expected and Texas at 4.26. But there was 12 mph wind blowing out to center field at 55\u00b0F, and that's exactly the kind of condition that can turn mistake pitches into extra-base hits. The model may have underweighted how much that outflow would impact a game between two offenses shaking off winter.\n\nThe one winner was **Rockies @ Miami UNDER 8.0**, which hit comfortably at 7 runs despite both starters carrying ugly expected marks in the 4.40-4.70 range.\n\n## WHAT TO WATCH\n\nOpening day totals are notoriously volatile as pitchers work into game shape. The model's closing line value was flat across the board (0.000), so we weren't fighting bad numbers \u2014 just got caught on the wrong side of variance and possibly underweighted wind conditions in the Philadelphia game.",
